# 3. いざ、勉強会！

Rui: Well then, let's begin our study session.
Akito, An & Tsukasa: Thank you for doing this!
Mizuki: But, how are we actually gonna teach them?
Rui: There's a test on the final day of the supplementary classes, yes?
Rui: The content of the classes must be targeted at that. Could I take a look at the worksheets you received in class?
Mizuki: Sure, here you go.
Rui: Thank you. Hmm...
Rui: I see. It seems the bulk of the questions cover the fundamentals of each subject. While there's a lot here, there are no complicated tests of applied knowledge.
Toya: That may be intentional on the part of the teachers since the goal of the test is to prevent students from being held back.
Tsukasa: Now that you mention it, the physics questions I answered were mostly basic knowledge.
Akito: So were mine. Although, I still flunked the test.
An: Yeah, me too.
Rui: What this means is that all you need to do is become able to solve all the problems in your worksheets.
Rui: How about this, then? We'll spend time focusing on the topics covered by the worksheets you each received.
Rui: You'll go back over each worksheet, while using the exercises in the textbook for particularly weak areas.
Rui: And if you encounter anything you don't understand, you can ask us three for help.
An: O-Okay...!
Mizuki: Oh, but will we definitely be able to help them out? What about you Toya? Do you have any weak subjects?
Toya: As I recall, Shiraishi failed classics and chemistry, while Akito failed English and math.
Toya: I'll have no trouble with basic questions for those four subjects. How about you, Akiyama?
Mizuki: Yep, those subjects are no trouble for me!
Rui: Also, when we teachers have spare time, we should review upcoming topics and be ready to answer questions.
Toya: Understood.
An: Thank you all...! I'm gonna try my best!
Mizuki: Great! Now, let's get this study session started!
An: Uh... “The chaunginge of the sesoun...stirreth the pathos of thinges...in alle manere wyse...”
An: (Urgh... Just like in class, I don't understand it at all.)
An: (It's just a non-starter every time since I don't even get the meaning of the sentence...)
An: (For now, I'd better try reading on...)
An: “And autumpne stirreth it most of al...oft it hath bin said...”
An: “Forsooth...it may be so...yit nought...can enflame the...herte...as can...”
An: (“Enflame”... Like getting fired up? But what does “forsooth” mean...?)
An: (Urgh... What the heck!)
An: I really don't get this at all! Is this seriously something a Japanese person wrote?!
Tsukasa: I understand what you mean...
Akito: You can't just read that stuff intuitively.
Mizuki: Hahaha... The thing with Classical Japanese is that you won't get very far unless you build up your vocabulary first.
Mizuki: An, which words do you not know?
An: Uhh... Almost all of them?
Mizuki: All of them... Okay, let's break it down!
Mizuki: So the first line is... “The chaunginge of the sesoun stirreth the pathos of thinges in alle manere wyse.” Is there anything there you want me to explain?
An: Yes! What's the “pathos of thinges”?
Mizuki: Hmm... It's like a feeling you get when something is rich in charm. We'd say “pathos of things” in modern times.
An: When something has charm... That's a phrase I hear a lot, but come to think of it, I don't know exactly what it means.
Toya: In other words, it's profoundly elegant. However, that may be somewhat abstract as a definition.
Rui: It might be easier to look through the lens of your lived experience. For example...
Rui: Shiraishi, have you ever been captivated by the sky at dusk?
An: The sky? At dusk...?
An: Oh! Sometimes, at the end of a day of singing practice, I'll feel really tired, look at the sky and think it looks gorgeous!
Tsukasa: Oh, I understand that too! When I look at the sky after pushing myself to the limit, it always looks so vast and peaceful.
An: Yes! I know exactly what you mean!
Rui: Hehe. That deeply sentimental feeling is more or less what is called “the pathos of things”.
An: Oh, I see...
Mizuki: And “sesoun” is an old way to say “season”...
Mizuki: As for “alle manere wyse”... It basically means “in all sorts of ways.”
An: So that means...
An: The changing seasons...lend a rich charm to everything?
Mizuki: Yeah! You got it!
An: Whoa! Thanks, you guys! I finally get what it means.
Rui: There you go, Shiraishi. You're getting a knack for this.
Akito: Well, she can read one line, at least.
Toya: Thank you for the input, Akito. Have you finished your own exercises? I haven't seen your pen move in a while.
Akito: *Wince*
Mizuki: Hahaha! Guess you're in the lead, An! Let's keep this up.
An: Yeah!
Tsukasa: Sorry, Rui! Help me! I'm utterly lost!
Rui: Let's see... You'll arrive at the answer if you apply the formula. Do you remember it?
Tsukasa: Um... I may have a recollection... Sorry. Can you explain it from the basics?
Akito: Urgh... I don't even get what this says.
Akito: Sine? Cosine? Tangent? Even if I learn what these words mean, they won't help me...
Toya: Relax, Akito. First, look at the lengths of two sides of the triangle. From there, you can start working out the answers.
Toya: We'll work through them all, together.
An: Um, so... This word means...“wonderful” or “rare”...
An: And this one means “excellent”...
An: What the... The word for “shameful” used to mean “impressive”?!
Mizuki: Hahaha, you can do it! The most important thing to do now is learn the most common words.
An: Ngh... They're not sinking in at all...
Rui: Oh, look at the time. I think you're all getting tired, so let's call it a day.
Tsukasa: It's finally over...
Akito: My head hurts...
Toya: That's proof of how hard you've been working. And, to absorb what you've learned today more effectively, you can review it before you go to bed tonight.
Akito: You gotta be kidding me...
An: Urgh, I don't wanna think anymore...
An: (But... I have to do this...)
An: (I will pass the test, and I will get into second year with the others!)
